SIMPLE: shy
RECORDS: 4

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Shy
<hw>Shy</hw> <pr>(sh⟦imac⟧)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos>
<amorph>[<pos>Compar.</pos> <adjf>Shier</adjf>
<pr>(sh⟦imac⟧"⟦etil⟧r)</pr> or <adjf>Shyer</adjf>; <pos>superl.</pos>
<adjf>Shiest</adjf> or <adjf>Shyest</adjf>.]</amorph> <ety>[OE.
<ets>schey</ets>, <ets>skey</ets>, <ets>sceouh</ets>, AS.
<ets>sce⟦oacute⟧h</ets>; akin to Dan. <ets>sky</ets>, Sw.
<ets>skygg</ets>, D. <ets>schuw</ets>, MHG. <ets>schiech</ets>, G.
<ets>scheu</ets>, OHG. <ets>sciuhen</ets> to be or make timid. Cf.
<er>Eschew</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>Easily frightened; timid;
<as>as, a <ex>shy</ex> bird</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The horses of the army . . . were no longer <qex>shy</qex>, but
would come up to my very feet without starting.</q>
<rj><qau>Swift.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Reserved; coy; disinclined to familiar
approach.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>What makes you so <qex>shy</qex>, my good friend? There's nobody
loves you better than I.</q> <rj><qau>Arbuthnot.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The embarrassed look of <qex>shy</qex> distress⟦br⟧
And maidenly shamefacedness.</q> <rj><qau>Wordsworth.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>Cautious; wary; suspicious.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>I am very <qex>shy</qex> of using corrosive liquors in the
preparation of medicines.</q> <rj><qau>Boyle.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Princes are, by wisdom of state, somewhat <qex>shy</qex> of thier
successors.</q> <rj><qau>Sir H. Wotton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>Inadequately supplied; short; lacking; <as>as, the
team is <ex>shy</ex> two players</as>.</def><mark>[Slang]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>Webster 1913 Suppl.</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <fld>(Poker)</fld>, <def>owing money to the pot; -- in
cases where an opponent's bet has exceeded a player's available stake or
chips, but the player chooses to continue playing the hand before adding
the required bet to the pot.</def> <mark>[Slang]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>To fight shy</b></col>. <cd>See under <er>Fight</er>,
<pos>v. i.</pos></cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Shy</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Shy
<hw>Shy</hw>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos>
<conjf>Shied</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Shying</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[From <er>Shy</er>,
<pos>a.</pos>]</ety> <def>To start suddenly aside through fright or
suspicion; -- said especially of horses.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Shy</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Shy
<hw>Shy</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <def>To throw sidewise with a jerk; to
fling; <as>as, to <ex>shy</ex> a stone; to <ex>shy</ex> a
slipper</as>.</def> <rj><au>T. Hughes.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Shy</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 4 ====
HEADWORD: Shy
<hw>Shy</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>A sudden start aside, as by
a horse.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A side throw; a throw; a fling.</def>
<rj><au>Thackeray.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>If Lord Brougham gets a stone in his hand, he must, it seems, have
a <qex>shy</qex> at somebody.</q> <rj><qau>Punch.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Shyly</ent>⟦br⟧
